    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nCurrently, if you attach multiple `virt_lines` extmarks to the same line, they're rendered in the order: 1, n, n-1, n-2, ...\n\nThis behavior persists even if `priority` is set to different values.\n\nHere's a quick demo, just source this file, you should see\n\n```\none\nfour\nthree\ntwo\n```\n\n```lua\n\nlocal ns = vim.api.nvim_create_namespace(\"z\")\n\nlocal function vl(text, prio)\n  vim.api.nvim_buf_set_extmark(0, ns, 0, 0, {\n    virt_lines = { { { text, \"\" } } },\n    priority = prio,\n  })\nend\n\nvl(\"one\")\nvl(\"two\")\nvl(\"three\")\nvl(\"four\")\n\n-- optionally set priority, which has no effect.\n-- vl(\"one\", 10)\n-- vl(\"two\", 12)\n-- vl(\"three\", 13)\n-- vl(\"four\", 14)\n\nvim.print(vim.api.nvim_buf_get_extmarks(0, ns, 0, -1, { details = true }))\n```\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nExtmarks have a `priority` field that effects the draw order of \"regular\" `virt_text`, why not have it effect `virt_lines` too? Higher priority drawn last (at the bottom)",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Sorry to bother, but this seems to be a part of the bigger issue, because not just `virt_lines` are resolved in this specific pattern of `[1,4,3,2]`. Specifically because `marktree_getp_aux()` currently searches for the first similar mark instead of the last one, and often ignores `priority` altogether.\n\nDetails are here: <https://github.com/neovim/neovim/discussions/37020#discussioncomment-15294146>",
